tp://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hLRr2rteN6s'),(3080,1080,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oj8QBSwAR8A'),(3086,1057,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Eqm3bEMhyto'),(3089,1053,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CkYydZ7F0wY'),(3092,1057,'_wp_old_slug','change-in-quantity-vs-change-in-supply2'),(3095,1044,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7pSc17Y-U10'),(3107,1047,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I47zkPzAKJU'),(3098,1041,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fqFIYYVwSb4'),(3110,1050,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Yw19ocTANRA'),(3101,875,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i6444GXZFbY'),(3126,1182,'description','A minimum price is a price floor that usually the government sets to prevent prices from falling to the equilibrium price. Example? In October 2011, the Thai government set a minimum price for commodity rubber at 120 bahts. This was done in part to protect the Thai farmers from a dip in rubber prices. Naturally this means that the equilibrium price is below 120 bahts, hence the government institutes a minimum price (or a price floor - no one is allowed to sell goods below this minimum price).\r\n\r\nThe minimum price has certain implications on welfare distribution. Like in the example, the minimum price usually protects producers - hence producer surplus is expected to increase. This is usually done at the expense of consumers. At the same time, because the market mechanism is being suspended, there will be allocative inefficiency happening - represented on the demand and supply diagram as the dead weight loss.\r\n\r\nWhen a minimum price is in place, since the price is artificially high, there will be a surplus (quantity supplied higher than quantity demanded) of rubber.'),(3104,869,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ITERc9Zw7qk'),(3113,862,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_3XlDF3qqLg'),(3125,1182,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Inl1QXTYrw0'),(3116,864,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jOpLA8Ud468'),(3119,866,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BN4qPYqqF1o'),(3144,1184,'description','A maximum price is a price ceiling - no one can trade above this price. In the States, specifically New York, the World War II veterans had no income (the war is over, no more military pay) but needed houses. Housing rent was rising rapidly then. Hence the government set a maximum price on the rent (also known as rent control). These ex-soldiers could then pay the rent, raise families and continue living in their homes that would otherwise be seized because they would not be able to pay the rents. However, say you were a house owner, will you be very willing to rent out your house after the government put a cap over how much you can earn from renting out the apartment? House owners then thought so too. Some went further - they were not willing to rent their houses out, instead hoping to wait till the rent control dies out. They hoard their supply! Hence the quantity demanded for housing increased (due to the low rent) and the quantity supplied decreased (because house owners were unwilling to rent out their houses). The available apartments were rapidly seized and there were none left for the late comers.\r\n\r\nSo like the minimum price, a maximum price distorts the market, creates allocative inefficiency and creates shortages. However, sometimes, the benefits of an immediate decrease in price (maximum prices can be rapidly implemented) far outweighs the welfare concerns and efficiency, as in the case of New York. These soldiers need houses!'),(3122,859,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Kow3f8NWIK4'),(3129,1176,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8ldYKQF7HMk'),(3130,1176,'description','In subsidies, we also talk about impact and incidence. Like taxation, the conclusion is that the more price inelastic the demand is for a good, the more the consumers enjoy the subsidies. Again, think intuitively. The more the consumer wants a good, the more subsidies he will grab from the producers. The opposite applies.'),(3143,1184,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OFZDppohPYQ'),(3135,1188,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=63WHNWOpzVw'),(3136,1188,'description','A quota is an absolute restriction on the AMOUNT (not price) of goods that can be traded. A ban is simply a quota set at zero. A famous example of the quota was the Prohibition in the United States, when trading and consuming alcohol was banned.\r\n\r\nLike maximum prices, quotas can lead to black markets occurring - as in the case of the Prohibition. In the classic novel Great Gatsby, the titular character Jay Gatsby accumulated his wealth by being a black marketeer who deals in alcohol during the Prohibition.\r\n\r\nThe quota also has certain implications for welfare, much like the welfare effects of the minimum price. However, quotas might not benefit the producers in all cases. Imagine that the quota comes in the form of a license issued by the government, and that the producers bid for the license to produce. Then, the increase in price that originally belonged to the producer will then belong to the government in the form of license revenue.'),(3139,1186,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t3rq3IJQE5U'),(3140,1186,'description','Black markets can occur when there is a maximum price. Since 2003, Venezuela President Hugo Chavez legislated (if it is even possible to do that properly in Venezuela) a price ceiling on food. Hence there is a constant shortage of food. In fact the price ceiling was brought into place because of rising food prices - itself being caused by sheer poverty, mismanagement by government and a series of bad harvests. Now imagine that you’re a profiteer who wishes to earn some money from the maximum price. You buy up a huge amount of food available at the low price, hoard it, then sell it at a high price. You can do that because the demand curve of consumers are much higher than the supply curve at any quantity below the equilibrium quantity. In other words, you start a black market. That is exactly what happens in Venezuela. The farmers themselves are unwilling to sell the food at the low price, instead preferring to sell it at a higher price in the black market.\r\n\r\nHence, the Associated Press reported that “Venezuelan troops are cracking down on the smuggling of food... the National Guard has seized about 750 tons of food... Hugo Chavez ordered the military to keep people from smuggling scarce items like milk... He\'s also threatened to seize farms and milk plants...” Chavez had to deal with the black market that resulted from the price ceiling.'),(3159,1170,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=csecV6rSESU'),(3147,1180,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h1sfvRpFCRQ'),(3148,1180,'description','Allocative efficiency is a concept that appears almost everywhere in microeconomics. The idea is that an economy attains allocative efficiency when it is producing the right type and amount of goods. In a demand and supply diagram, this happens when demand meets supply. This is where consumer and producers surplus are maximized. As you will see in the next few lectures, whenever certain controls (be it price controls or quotas) are in place, consumer and producer surplus will be reduced, leading to a loss of surplus that we indicate on the diagram as dead weight loss (a graphical representation of allocative inefficiency).\r\n\r\nGovernments often enact price controls (either in the form of minimum prices or maximum prices). Their purpose is to well, control prices. They override the market mechanism for price setting and introduce an artificial price that is either higher (in the case of a minimum price) or lower (in the case of a maximum price) than the original market equilibrium.'),(3160,1170,'description','The impact of a tax and the subsequent incidence of a tax are two very different things. The impact of the tax refers to the party on whom the tax is levied. So the GST is levied on the producers, because producers have to sell their goods 7% pricier. On the other hand, the incidence refers to the burden of the tax. This is a welfare concept; when we talk about incidence we are concerned about the eventual distribution of the burden of the tax.\r\n\r\nPED affects the incidence of taxation. The more price inelastic demand is, the more the consumer bears the burden. Intuitively, that is because the more the consumer wants the good (hence the more price inelastic a good is), the less his consumption pattern will change given price changes. Since he wants the good so much, he will be willing to pay the taxes to consume the goods.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, if the good has a price elastic demand and hence consumers are sensitive to price changes, the burden of the tax will not fall that much on the consumers. They will just choose not to consume it. Hence the burden of the tax falls more on producers.\r\n\r\nThis effect is important for policy makers who are concerned about the eventual welfare distributional effects of taxation.'),(3151,1178,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KcD1JCR0AkA'),(3152,1178,'description','Again like taxation, the PES of a good also affects how the incidence of subsidies are distributed. The more price inelastic the supply of a good is, the more the producers enjoy the subsidies. A producer that is very inflexible in supplying its goods will take most of the subsidies, vice versa.'),(3155,1172,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=csecV6rSESU'),(3156,1172,'description','Similarly PES affects the the incidence of taxation as well. The more price inelastic the supply of a producer is, the more he has to bear a tax. Think about this intuitively. Say that the producer sells a good with a very price inelastic demand. Since he cannot adjust his production according to the tax changes, he will have to bear the burden of the tax since he is the one not budging.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, a good with a price elastic demand should allow a producer to push to burden to consumers. This is because they are able to adjust their output flexibly according to taxation conditions. This flexibility prevents them from incurring the burden of the tax that would otherwise be borne if they were more rigid.'),(3163,1174,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L24_SwkB0D0'),(3164,1174,'description','Like taxation, for indirect subsidies, there are lump sum taxes and <em>ad valorem</em> (percentage) subsidy. The lump sum subsidy shifts the supply curve vertically downwards because the producer will be willing to sell goods at each quantity at a lower price by a fixed amount. The percentage subsidy effects a pivoted shift on the supply curve because at higher prices, the price goes down by a higher absolute amount.'),(3167,1166,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QSJye_FuG8E'),(3168,1166,'description','Here we introduce the two types of taxation: direct and indirect. Direct taxes are tax payments paid directly to the government. In the case of Singapore, the agency responsible for that is the Inland Revenue Authority of Singapore (IRAS). An example of a direct tax is the income tax. The income tax is paid directly to the government by income earners. \r\n\r\nOn the other hand, for indirect tax, the payment is made when purchasing certain goods. For example, when a person in Singapore buys groceries for $10, $0.70 of that is paid to the government as Goods and Services Tax (GST). This is a form of indirect tax because the tax isn’t paid directly to the government, but levied when the person (in the case of the GST, the consumer) buys something.\r\n\r\nDirect taxation does not shift the supply curve. However, indirect taxation does because it increases the price at which producers are willing to supply their goods at every quantity. This increase can be either a parallel shift (as in the case of a lump sum tax) or a pivoted shift (for <em>ad valorem</em> or percentage taxes).'),(3196,1108,'description','Price Elasticity of Supply is defined as “the responsiveness of the quantity supplied of a good to a change in its price, <em>ceteris paribus</em>.” The question you ask when you apply PES is “If I increase the price of a product, how much more can producers supply?” This is an important measure from the producers’ perspective.'),(3171,1122,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=44VFMP7f7S4'),(3172,1122,'description','So occasionally, case study questions will ask you to calculate these elasticities, or how much the quantity demanded/supplied of a good will change if some other factor varies. These formula will be extremely useful then. The video is pretty self explanatory.'),(3175,1120,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nW2MF9-Jdhg'),(3176,1120,'description','Cross Elasticity of Demand and Income Elasticity of Demands have their applications as well. A CEO will definitely be concerned with CED. The need for YED is pretty evident as well. The applications are rather straight forward. Just watch the video.'),(3179,1118,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=78_p3tPqR3A'),(3180,1118,'description','There are two main reasons for government taxation (and they are not mutually exclusive). 1. Taxation revenue (the government needs money to build public infrastructure and pay its civil servants) and 2. Correcting consumption patterns (slamming a hefty tax on alcohol to discourage people downing vodka).\r\n\r\nPED is relevant in both these cases. For the first case, the revenue example from the previous lecture segment applies. For the second case, it should be pretty evident as well. Let’s say that plastic bags have a price elastic demand (they are easily substitutable by other more environmentally sustainable bags, and sometimes they are not necessary at all). So if the government slams a tax on the use of plastic bags, we can expect the quantity demanded for plastic bags to fall more than proportionately and rather significantly. This is effective in reducing consumption.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, for something like cigarettes with a price inelastic demand, the tax will not reduce consumption significantly (because your smoke addicts will still want to take puffs). Hence a large amount of taxation will need to be levied to change consumption patterns significantly. However, this also means that cigarettes are a good source of taxation for many governments because despite the high taxation, quantity demanded for cigarettes do not decrease by too much, hence tax revenue stays high.'),(3195,1108,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hLSyA6TPnxw'),(3183,1116,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fHcfPOwnBGI'),(3184,1116,'description','One of the primary applications of PED is in price setting and revenues. If you are the boss of a company and you have a good that has a price inelastic demand, you can afford to raise the price and earn more revenue because when you raise the price, the quantity demanded does fall. However, the quantity demanded falls LESS than proportionately than price. Since revenue = price x quantity, revenue actually increases when quantity decreases because it decreases less than proportionately compared to the price. So for example, when a good has a PED of 0.1 and the price increases by 50% (remember it is always percentage increase, not absolute increase that we are concerned with in elasticity analysis), the quantity demanded will decrease by 5%. Revenue will increase because\r\n\r\nNew revenue = 1.5 x Original Price x 0.95 x Original Quantity = 1.425 x Original Revenue\r\n\r\nThe reverse applies for a good with a price elastic demand. Try it!'),(3187,1114,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=poP7h5uBH5c'),(3188,1114,'description','The PES of a good helps us decide whether a good has an elastic or inelastic supply. However, what determines that PES in the first place? These are some of the common determinants of PES.'),(3191,1110,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R1FZRN0aXD8'),(3192,1110,'description','Price Elasticity of Supply is usually positive; suppliers are willing to produce more as prices goes up, hence quantity supplied moves in the same direction as price. This gives the positive coefficient for PES (unless PES is 0, which denotes a perfectly inelastic supply). When the PES is between 0 and 1, this means that the supply curve in question is relatively inelastic. When it is 1, it is unit elastic. More than 1, relatively elastic. When it is infinite, the supply curve is perfectly elastic. The same concept as PED applies here.'),(3199,1090,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UFqLxIm6Zzo'),(3200,1090,'description','Elasticity in economics is basically concerned with the question \"how much will A change if I vary B?\". It is a measure of how one economic variable affects another. Hence, some of the questions that we will ask during the course of learning elasticities are \"how many more goods will I sell if I lower my price\" or \"if I raise my price, how much less will I sell\". For this series of lectures, we will introduce 4 kinds of elasticities: Price Elasticity of Demand (PED), Income Elasticity of Demand (YED), Cross Elasticity of Demand (CED) and Price Elasticity of Supply (PES).\r\n\r\nElasticities are important because not knowing them will definitely bar you from even a C in economics. I kid. However, they are indeed important in economics; they allow us to understand the operations of a firm, the effects of taxation, welfare distribution and many other effects. Just imagine that you’re the Tim Cook, CEO of Apple. (Everything in economics in simplified. Bear with me). You’re thinking of lowering the price of iPhones. A good question to ask will be: how many more iPhones will I sell now that I’ve lowered its price? This matters because if I sell a lot more iPhones now, much more than the percentage the price lowered, then my revenue (which is Price times Quantity) will increase. Now imagine that you’re a bureaucrat in the Singapore Government deliberating on the effectiveness of fat tax (tax imposed on fatty and unhealthy food). If you can prove that increasing taxes causes a large drop in consumption, then you can prove that the tax is effective. \r\n\r\nThese are just some of the many applications of elasticities. For the first part of this lecture series, we will define the 4 elasticities and provide some simple applications and examples. For the second part, we will explore the applications of these elasticities in much more detail.'),(3213,1096,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=02P0PxW07dQ'),(3203,1092,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A6d_1FCzTyI'),(3204,1092,'description','Here’s a tip. To do explanations without missing out on major points, always use frameworks. For elasticities, always identify 3 main things when explaining them in a question:\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>The definition of the elasticity. e.g. For PED, it is “the responsiveness of quantity demanded of a good to a change in its price, <em>ceteris paribus</em></li>\r\n<li>The sign of the coefficient of the elasticity e.g. For PED, the sign of the coefficient is always negative (because quantity demanded increases when price decreases)</li>\r\n<li>The value of the coefficient of the elasticity e.g. A price inelastic good has a low value for the coefficient</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThis is the framework that we use for explaining elasticities.\r\n\r\nYou will encounter the term “<em>ceteris paribus</em>” very often. This is Latin for \"with other things the same.\" You can interpret this to mean that the whole world stays constant except for the two variables in question. The concept of “<em>ceteris paribus</em>” is in itself potentially misleading – simply because the world never stays still. However, for the purposes of economic modelling and simplification in analysis, the <em>ceteris paribus</em> clause is extremely useful. \r\n\r\nFor the science students, think of it as serving a similar purpose as the “assume that there is no friction” clause in Physics examinations, or the fact that in Chemistry questions you are assumed to have superhuman precision in mixing reagents. Imagine doing a chemical reaction question when you have to take into account the shakiness of the scientist’s hands, the cleanliness of the flask, minute temperature differences in the surrounding areas. These variables do change in real life. However, we assume them away simply because they don’t affect the results much. Likewise in Economics, we use the “<em>ceteris paribus</em>” clause to shut out variables that we assume insignificant to the question at hand.'),(3207,1094,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UkC8lrfBWb8'),(3208,1094,'description','Price Elasticity of Demand is defined as “the responsiveness of the quantity demand of a good to a change in its price, <em>ceteris paribus</em>”. Hence the question you ask when you apply PED to a question is \"how much will the quantity demanded of a good change when I toggle the price of that good\".\r\n\r\nGiven that a demand curve slopes downwards most of the time, the coefficient of PEDs are negative. This means that when you increase the price of a good, the quantity demand always moves in the opposite direction i.e. decrease.'),(3214,1096,'description','A good with a PED > 1 means that the good has a price elastic demand. When the price changes, the quantity demand changes more than proportionately. Think of it this way. The VALUE of coefficient of the PED measures the number of times the quantity demand will change with respect to the price. So if a good has a PED of 2, it simply means that when the price of the good increases by 40%, the quantity demanded of the good will decrease by 80%. This means that the quantity demanded changes more than proportionately with respect to price. Hence it is price elastic.\r\n\r\nJust think in terms of the opposite for a price inelastic demand. Try it. If you still can’t figure that out, ask!'),(3217,1098,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r3OKEa2rtuc'),(3218,1098,'description','The PED of a good determines if a good has a price elastic or price inelastic demand. However, what are the factors that determine the PED in the first place? (No it is not whether the good has a price elastic or inelastic demand. That’s circular reasoning). These are the 4 main factors that affect the PED of a good.'),(3233,1106,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JT36amNvwO8'),(3221,1100,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7tciNQ6tVHE'),(3222,1100,'description','The YED of a good is defined as “the responsiveness of the demand of a good to a change in one’s income, <em>ceteris paribus</em>.” Note that instead of “quantity demanded”, the definition invokes only “demand”. This is because PED concerns itself with movements along a fixed demand curve. Questions like how much will the quantity demand increase if I decrease the price and vice versa concern themselves with only one single demand curve.\r\n\r\nHowever, for the YED, we ask how much will the DEMAND CURVE shift when one’s income changes. A YED of 3 (positive 3, not negative 3) will mean that when one’s income increases by 40%, the DEMAND of the good will increase by 120%.'),(3225,1102,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GSLq4-K51Zs'),(3226,1102,'description','The coefficient of YED can be either positive or negative. A good with a positive YED is a positive good. Why so? Think about this. The demand of a YED positive good must increase when one’s income increases. That means a person consumes more of that good when his income increases. That practically applies for most goods we know. However, what about things like broken rice? (Rice that’s left over and broken during the harvesting and packing process.) When people get richer, they consume less of broken rice because they switch to proper rice. Because better products are available, consumers buy less of the lousy rice. Broken rice and many other goods that behave this way are called inferior goods. The demand of inferior goods decrease when one’s income increases. Similarly, their demand increase when one’s income decreases. It is then called an inferior good.\r\n\r\nThere are two types of normal goods – luxury and necessity. While they both have a YED of > 0, luxury goods have YED > 1 while necessities have 0 < YED < 1. This is because when your income increases, you’d consume a lot more luxury goods (you can afford more perks now!) However, the amount of necessities you can consume are limited (how much more rice can you eat even if you get rich!). Hence demand for necessities increase less than proportionately when income increases.'),(3234,1106,'description','The coefficient of CED can either be positive, negative or zero. Think about it this way. The quantity demanded of Good B moves in the opposite direction as the price of Good B. That means when the price of Good B increases, the quantity demanded of Good B decreases. If the demand of Good A increases (i.e. Move in the same direction as Good B’s PRICE), then Good A is a substitute of Good B. Good B price increases, consumers buy less because Good B is more expensive. Good B’s quantity demanded drops, and consumers switch to Good A, hence increasing the demand of Good A. Hence, when the demand of Good A moves in the same direction as the Price of Good B (and in opposite direction as the quantity demanded of Good B), then Good A is a substitute for Good B. The same logic works when the Price of Good B decreases. The demand of Good A should then decrease if Good A is a substitute for Good B.\r\n \r\nHowever, when the price of Good B increases and the demand of Good A decreases, they are complements. Think of cameras and camera lenses. The quantity demanded for cameras decreases when the price of cameras increases because less people can afford them. For most professional cameras, a photographer will also need a good lens to go with the camera; i.e. To enjoy the benefits of having a camera, one will also need a camera lens. Camera lenses and camera are hence complements. Hence when the quantity demanded for cameras decrease, the demand for camera lenses will decrease. The demand for camera lenses just moved in an opposite direction as the price of cameras. This happens to complements.\r\n\r\nWhen two goods have CED zero, this just means that they are unrelated. Simple\r\n \r\nFor both complements and substitutes, there are strong and weak ones. This then concerns the value of the CED. When the absolute value of a CED is > 1, it is a strong complement / substitute. When the absolute value is 0 < CED < 1, it is a weak complement / substitute because the demand of Good A moves less than proportionately when the price of Good B changes.'),(3229,1104,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_QnKL1SLsS4'),(3230,1104,'description','Cross Elasticity of Demand is defined as “the responsiveness of the demand of Good A to a change in the price of Good B, <em>ceteris paribus</em>.” The question you are asking when you use CED is “if I change the price of Good B, what happens to measure he demand of Good A?” The businessmen among should appreciate the importance of this already. Just imagine competition between two firms! McDonald\'s will definitely want to know what happens if Carl\'s Jr changes its prices.'),(3240,1265,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=46DtPa5s59A'),(3237,1263,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UC7MqHW1A6A'),(3243,1267,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CMlOmA_KMMI'),(3246,1277,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iFHkZwUvKPI'),(3249,1275,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tG30O65s8pQ'),(3252,1281,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aETu_XxRbk4'),(3255,1279,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=piC5rrbSQWs'),(3260,1273,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bi_JqBhsOkw'),(3263,1271