i talks about how subsidies can affect externalities.'),(3564,1623,'description','Most of the time, people will buy less of something if you make it more expensive by throwing taxes on it. If you swap that something with a good that is socially undesirable (say cigarettes), then people should consume less of it. That is how taxes can be used to solve externalities. In this lecture, Zhou Penghui elaborates on this concept.'),(3567,1620,'description','A government is usually the one providing public goods like natio.nal defense. Zhou Penghui elaborates on them in this lecture'),(3571,2957,'_wp_attached_file','profile_nigel.png'),(3570,1617,'description','When the invisible hand fails, the visible hand takes over. For those of you less familiar with these econo-lingo (animal spirits, random walks, invisible hands, helicopters), that sentence means \"when the free market fails, the government takes over\". \r\n\r\nIn this set of lectures, we explore the various ways governments can correct market failures.'),(3572,2957,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:6:{s:5:\"width\";s:3:\"200\";s:6:\"height\";s:3:\"240\";s:14:\"hwstring_small\";s:22:\"height=\'96\' width=\'80\'\";s:4:\"file\";s:17:\"profile_nigel.png\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:1:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:3:{s:4:\"file\";s:25:\"profile_nigel-150x150.png\";s:5:\"width\";s:3:\"150\";s:6:\"height\";s:3:\"150\";}}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:10:{s:8:\"aperture\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";s:1:\"0\";s:9:\"copyright\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"focal_length\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"iso\";s:1:\"0\";s:13:\"shutter_speed\";s:1:\"0\";s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";}}'),(3573,2960,'_wp_attached_file','profile_casatrina.png'),(3574,2960,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:6:{s:5:\"width\";s:3:\"200\";s:6:\"height\";s:3:\"240\";s:14:\"hwstring_small\";s:22:\"height=\'96\' width=\'80\'\";s:4:\"file\";s:21:\"profile_casatrina.png\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:1:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:3:{s:4:\"file\";s:29:\"profile_casatrin