,(3614,2985,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:6:{s:5:\"width\";s:3:\"200\";s:6:\"height\";s:3:\"240\";s:14:\"hwstring_small\";s:22:\"height=\'96\' width=\'80\'\";s:4:\"file\";s:17:\"profile_junle.png\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:1:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:3:{s:4:\"file\";s:25:\"profile_junle-150x150.png\";s:5:\"width\";s:3:\"150\";s:6:\"height\";s:3:\"150\";}}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:10:{s:8:\"aperture\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";s:1:\"0\";s:9:\"copyright\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"focal_length\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"iso\";s:1:\"0\";s:13:\"shutter_speed\";s:1:\"0\";s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";}}'),(3653,1229,'description','You have been taught till now that the market works in wonderful ways. Consumers and producers determine prices of products by how much they value those products and how much the products cost. The interaction of these two forces then produce a market price which then signals to the consumer and the producer how much to produce. These incentives produce a socially optimal outcome without anyone having to determine the price or output quantity in the market. Sadly, reality is not all that rosy. There is always market failure.'),(3656,1231,'description','Most lecturers at Open Lectures love Apple. Linan, Yitao, Kenneth, Kangjie, Gary and Yongjian all use Macs. However, Apple is a monopoly. When it is a monopoly, it does certain nasty things - like making the iPhone software more closed than a prison cell, marking up Mac prices significantly. There are many other such monopolies in real life. Together, they are a form of market failure.'),(3659,1233,'description','Externalities is defined as the additional cost / benefit incurred by a 3rd party, an entity who is not the person or firm consuming or producing the good. Externalities add a whole new dimension to cost benefit analysis. Zhou Penghui tells you more.'),(3662,1235,'description','A factory expelling toxic waste upstream causes damage to people who use the water downstream. Another example can be your neighbor. Your neighbor playing kinetic frustrates you. However the only cost that he incurs for himself is his sore legs (and probably the kinect set). The noise he produces is an additional cost borne by a third party (in this case, you!). \r\n\r\nZhou Penghui gives you even more examples of negative externalities.'),(3665,1237,'description','There are positive externalities as well! Take for example a school. By providing a person with basic education, that person can learn basic social protocols, communicate effectively and eventually find a job for himself. These are benefits he rack up for himself. However, by putting him through primary school, he also learns basic social protocol and language skills. This allows him to contribute to society and function cohesively in a society, hence clocking up external benefits socially.'),(3668,1239,'description','Will you ever pay for national defense? Yes? But let\'s say you pay. Your neighbor can just not pay but still enjoy the same benefits (since the army must protect the entire nation, not just your house). Since he can free ride and still get the goods, why not you free ride as well? Now think. Will anyone still pay? If no one pays, will a private enterprise ever provide that good? This leads to the dilemma of public goods.'),(3669,1060,'_wp_page_template','default'),(3670,3023,'_edit_last','1'),(3671,3023,'_edit_lock','1325684378:1'),(3680,3027,'_edit_lock','1325684243:1'),(3674,3023,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SYDTs_PFMBg'),(3679,3027,'_edit_last','1'),(3687,3030,'_edit_lock','1325684308:1'),(3683,3027,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f4yIj-Kvams'),(3686,3030,'_edit_last','1'),(3692,3032,'_edit_lock','1325684375:1'),(3691,3032,'_edit_last','1'),(3690,3030,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=04mPJ3YU1xs'),(3697,3034,'_edit_lock','1325684413:1'),(3696,3034,'_edit_last','1'),(3695,3032,'videourl','http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=73H10