aking small, regular deposits in this bank of experience: education and training. And on January 15 the balance was sufficient so that I could make a very large withdrawal.”<br></br><small>Captain Sullenberger, pilot who landed the US Airway Flight 1549 in the Hudson River during an emergency</small></blockquote>\r\nHow would you make your withdrawal? We know that you do not want your time to be squandered meaninglessly. Through a combination of your own intellect and the generous endowments given to you by the education system, you became the best. Do you feel the need to give back something to your juniors - something less ephemeral than one passing lesson to a select group of students.\r\n\r\nWe can’t give you the answers, but if you found some yourself, we want to hear from you. Meet us for a cup of coffee (on us of course) and allow us to get to know you. We’ll help you get the meaningful teaching experience you deserve.','Graduates','','draft','open','closed','','graduates','','','2011-10-29 20:20:10','2011-10-29 12:20:10','',0,'http://openlectures.sg/wordpress/?page_id=965',0,'page','',0),(2071,1,'2011-09-15 21:47:09','2011-09-15 13:47:09','<h3>No one should pay exorbitant prices for education</h3>\r\nBaumol’s cost disease is a term used to describe the phenomenon where salaries rise in jobs that experience no increase in productivity. Coined by William Baumol, an influential American economist, the term aptly describes the job of a tuition teacher. Ten years ago, one tuition teacher taught at most a few students. The tuition teacher today does the same but for higher prices.\r\n\r\nWe don’t think that should be the way things work nor the way you as a parent should allocate your money. There must be better ways for your child to revise certain topics, clarify some misconceptions and go through reruns of lectures without invoking costly tuition expenses.\r\n\r\nThis is why we created Open Lectures. Through us, your child can gain access to top quality lecture