','',1245,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/1245-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(3147,1,'2012-01-01 11:52:31','2012-01-01 03:52:31','','[04] Circular Flow of Income','','inherit','open','open','','1247-revision-3','','','2012-01-01 11:52:31','2012-01-01 03:52:31','',1247,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/1247-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(1057,13,'2011-09-18 09:55:07','2011-09-18 01:55:07','','Change in Quantity vs. Change in Supply','','draft','open','open','','change-in-quantity-vs-change-in-supply','','','2012-01-23 10:07:16','2012-01-23 02:07:16','',0,'http://openlectures.sg/?p=1057',8,'post','',0),(3090,1,'2011-12-30 00:13:45','2011-12-29 16:13:45','','Producer Surplus','','inherit','open','open','','1050-revision','','','2011-12-30 00:13:45','2011-12-29 16:13:45','',1050,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/1050-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(1059,1,'2011-09-18 09:55:07','2011-09-18 01:55:07','','Change in Quantity vs. Change in Supply','','inherit','open','open','','change-in-quantity-vs-change-in-supply-3','','','2011-09-18 09:55:07','2011-09-18 01:55:07','',1057,'',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1060,1,'2011-09-18 10:04:44','2011-09-18 02:04:44','        <div class=\"row\">\r\n          <div class=\"span-one-third\">\r\n            <p style=\"text-align:center;\"><a href=\"/subjects/economics/theory-of-the-firm/\"><img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/Theory_of_the_firm.png\"></a></p>\r\n            <h2>Theory of the Firm</h2>\r\n            <p>There are many ways to make money - sell awesome products, scam people, adopt violence or sell iPhone imitations. All of them involve revenues, costs and profits. That’s where Theory of the Firm comes in.</p>\r\n            <p><a class=\"btn\" target=\"_self\" href=\"/subjects/economics/theory-of-the-firm/\">View Lectures &raquo;</a></p>\r\n          </div>\r\n          <div class=\"span-one-third\">\r\n            <p style=\"text-align:center;\"><a href=\"/subjects/economics/demand-supply/\"><img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/Demand_and_supply.png\"></a></p>\r\n            <h2>Demand and Supply</h2>\r\n            <p>You probably heard of these two words way before you even started learning economics, because they drive practically everything in microeconomics - be it prices, amount traded, how happy your consumers are and how much your producer earns.</p>\r\n            <p><a class=\"btn\" href=\"/subjects/economics/demand-supply/\">View Lectures &raquo;</a></p>\r\n         </div>\r\n\r\n          <div class=\"span-one-third\">\r\n            <p style=\"text-align:center;\"><a href=\"/subjects/economics/elasticities/\"><img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/Elasticities.png\"></a></p>\r\n            <h2>Elasticities</h2>\r\n            <p>“To what extent will something change when something else changes?” This seemingly small question has huge implications. Interested? Well you might be interested to know that the second sentence itself in this paragraph is an elasticity expression.</p>\r\n            <p><a class=\"btn\" href=\"/subjects/economics/elasticities/\">View Lectures &raquo;</a></p>\r\n          </div>\r\n        </div>\r\n\r\n        <hr>\r\n\r\n        <div class=\"row\">\r\n          <div class=\"span-one-third\">\r\n            <p style=\"text-align:center;\"><a href=\"/subjects/economics/market-structure/\"><img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/Market_structure.png\"></a></p>\r\n            <h2>Market Structures</h2>\r\n            <p>Is there a difference between Apple Inc. and the grocery store round the corner? Or a 7-Eleven chain and the provision store that just got taken over by a 7-Eleven? Does the Monopoly board game actually mean anything close to that? By the way that game is actually far more of an oligopoly.</p>\r\n            <p><a class=\"btn\" href=\"/subjects/economics/market-structure/\">View Lectures &raquo;</a></p>\r\n          </div>\r\n\r\n          <div class=\"span-one-third\">\r\n            <p style=\"text-align:center;\"><a href=\"/subjects/economics/market-failure/\"><img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/Market_failure.png\"></a></p>\r\n            <h2>Market Failure</h2>\r\n             <p>The invisible hand gets carpal tunnel sometimes. It gets less nimble and more inaccurate. When that happens, things in the economy get allocated less efficiently. Some people exploit these: and hence, “if you’re quick with the knife, the invisible hand is full of invisible delicious meat.”</p>\r\n            <p><a class=\"btn\" href=\"/subjects/economics/market-failure/\">View Lectures &raquo;</a></p>\r\n         </div>\r\n\r\n          <div class=\"span-one-third\"/>\r\n            <p style=\"text-align:center;\"><a href=\"/subjects/economics/government-intervention/\"><img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/Government_intervention.png\"></a></p>\r\n            <h2>Government Intervention</h2>\r\n            <p>This is where we heal the invisible hand with carpal tunnel - by applying creams and ointments. These lubricants, in economics, come in the form of government intervention. They soothe where it hurts - be it externalities, public goods or imperfect competition.</p>\r\n            <p><a class=\"btn\" href=\"/subjects/economics/government-intervention/\">View Lectures &raquo;</a></p>\r\n          </div>\r\n</div>\r\n<hr>\r\n        <div class=\"row\">\r\n          <div class=\"span-one-third\"/>\r\n            <p style=\"text-align:center;\"><a href=\"/subjects/economics/macroeconomic-aims/\"><img src=\"/wp-content/uploads/Macroeconomic_aims.png\"></a></p>\r\n            <h2>Macroeconomic Aims</h2>\r\n            <p>What are the big questions that governments have to ask? What will our economic growth be like? Are there enough jobs in the economy? Is our inflation healthy? Are we maintaining stable external relations with other countries?</p>\r\n            <p><a class=\"btn\" href=\"/subjects/economics/macroeconomic-aims/\">View Lectures &raquo;</a></p>\r\n          </div>\r\n        </div>','Economics','','private','open','closed','','economics','','','2012-01-04 20:22:13','2012-01-04 12:22:13','',0,'http://openlectures.sg/?page_id=1060',0,'page','',0),(1655,1,'2011-10-04 18:36:49','2011-10-04 10:36:49','Description Thumbnail','Theory of the Firm','Theory of the Firm','inherit','open','open','','theory_of_the_firm','','','2011-10-04 18:36:49','2011-10-04 10:36:49','',1060,'http://openlectures.sg/wp-content/uploads/Theory_of_the_firm.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(1078,13,'2011-09-18 16:45:19','2011-09-18 08:45:19','','Demand Increases, Supply Increases','','draft','open','open','','demand-increases-supply-increases','','','2012-01-23 10:07:16','2012-01-23 02:07:16','',0,'http://openlectures.sg/?p=1078',13,'post','',0),(2778,29,'2011-12-11 18:33:31','2011-12-11 10:33:31','','Consumer Surplus','','inherit','open','open','','1053-revision-3','','','2011-12-11 18:33:31','2011-12-11 10:33:31','',1053,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/1053-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(1561,1,'2011-10-01 10:44:49','2011-10-01 02:44:49','','Demand Increases, Supply Increases','','inherit','open','open','','demand-increases-supply-increases-2','','','2011-10-01 10:44:49','2011-10-01 02:44:49','',1078,'',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1080,13,'2011-09-18 16:45:42','2011-09-18 08:45:42','','Demand Decreases, Supply Decreases','','draft','open','open','','demand-decreases-supply-decreases','','','2012-01-23 10:07:15','2012-01-23 02:07:15','',0,'http://openlectures.sg/?p=1080',14,'post','',0),(3088,1,'2011-12-30 00:13:45','2011-12-29 16:13:45','','Change in Quantity vs. Change in Supply','','inherit','open','open','','1057-revision-2','','','2011-12-30 00:13:45','2011-12-29 16:13:45','',1057,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/1057-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(1563,1,'2011-10-01 10:45:19','2011-10-01 02:45:19','','Demand Decreases, Supply Decreases','','inherit','open','open','','demand-decreases-supply-decreases-2','','','2011-10-01 10:45:19','2011-10-01 02:45:19','',1080,'',0,'attachment','image/j