and','','inherit','open','open','','definitions-of-income-elasticity-of-demand-2','','','2011-09-29 20:12:08','2011-09-29 12:12:08','',1100,'',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2768,29,'2011-12-11 19:11:10','2011-12-11 11:11:10','','Determinants of Price Elasticity of Demand','','inherit','open','open','','1098-revision','','','2011-12-11 19:11:10','2011-12-11 11:11:10','',1098,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/1098-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(1479,1,'2011-09-29 20:12:59','2011-09-29 12:12:59','','Coefficients of Income Elasticity of Demand','','inherit','open','open','','coefficients-of-income-elasticity-of-demand-2','','','2011-09-29 20:12:59','2011-09-29 12:12:59','',1102,'',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1469,1,'2011-09-29 20:07:46','2011-09-29 12:07:46','','Framework for Analysing Elasticity','','inherit','open','open','','framework-for-analysing-elasticity-2','','','2011-09-29 20:07:46','2011-09-29 12:07:46','',1092,'',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1778,1,'2011-10-08 10:36:36','2011-10-08 02:36:36','httpvh://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A6d_1FCzTyI\n\nHere’s a tip. To do explanations without missing out on major points, always use frameworks. For elasticities, always identify 3 main things when explaining them in a question:\n<ol>\n<li>The definition of the elasticity. eg. For PED, it is “the responsiveness of quantity demanded of a good to a change in its price, <em>ceteris paribus</em></li>\n<li>The sign of the coefficient of the elasticity eg. For PED, the sign of the coefficient is always negative (because quantity demanded increases when price decreases)</li>\n<li>The value of the coefficient of the elasticity e.g. A price inelastic good has a low value for the coefficient</li>\n</ol>\nThis is the framework that we use for explaining elasticities.\n\nYou will encounter the term “ceteris paribus” very often. This is Latin for \"with other things the same.\" You can interpret this to mean that the whole world stays constant except for the two variables in question. The concept of “ceteris paribus” is in itself potentially misleading – simply because the world never stays still. However, for the purposes of economic modelling and simplification in analysis, the ceteris paribus clause is extremely useful. \n\nFor the science students, think of it as serving a similar purpose as the “assume that there is no friction” clause in Physics examinations, or the fact that in Chemistry questions you are assumed to have superhuman precision in mixing reagents. Imagine doing a chemical reaction question when you have to take into account the shakiness of the scientist’s hands, the cleanliness of the flask, minute temperature differences in the surrounding areas. These variables do change in real life. However, we assume them away simply because they don’t affect the results much. Likewise in Economics, we use the “ceteris paribus” clause to shut out variables that we assume insignificant to the question at hand.','Framework for Analysing Elasticity','','inherit','open','open','','1092-autosave','','','2011-10-08 10:36:36','2011-10-08 02:36:36','',1092,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/1092-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(1471,1,'2011-09-29 20:10:04','2011-09-29 12:10:04','','Definition of Price Elasticity of Demand','','inherit','open','open','','definition-of-price-elasticity-of-demand-2','','','2011-09-29 20:10:04','2011-09-29 12:10:04','',1094,'',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3195,1,'2011-12-30 00:13:44','2011-12-29 16:13:44','','Definition of Price Elasticity of Demand','','inherit','open','open','','1094-revision','','','2011-12-30 00:13:44','2011-12-29 16:13:44','',1094,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/1094-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(3249,1,'2012-01-23 20:20:23','2012-01-23 12:20:23','','[02] Limiting Reagents and Excess Reactants','','publish','open','open','','02-limiting-reagents-and-excess-reactants','','','2012-01-23 20:20:23','2012-01-23 12:20:23','',0,'http://openlectures.sg/?p=3249',0,'post','',0),(3250,1,'2012-01-23 20:20:19','2012-01-23 12:20:19','','[02] Limiting Reagents and Excess Reactants','','inherit','open','open','','3249-revision','','','2012-01-23 20:20:19','2012-01-23 12:20:19','',3249,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/3249-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(3251,1,'2012-01-23 20:20:56','2012-01-23 12:20:56','','[03] Types of Reactions','','publish','open','open','','03-types-of-reactions','','','2012-01-23 20:20:56','2012-01-23 12:20:56','',0,'http://openlectures.sg/?p=3251',0,'post','',0),(1473,1,'2011-09-29 20:10:50','2011-09-29 12:10:50','','Coefficients of Price Elasticity of Demand','','inherit','open','open','','coefficients-of-price-elasticity-of-demand-2','','','2011-09-29 20:10:50','2011-09-29 12:10:50','',1096,'',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2770,29,'2011-12-11 19:10:44','2011-12-11 11:10:44','','Definition of Price Elasticity of Demand','','inherit','open','open','','1094-revision-3','','','2011-12-11 19:10:44','2011-12-11 11:10:44','',1094,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/1094-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(1321,1,'2011-09-22 20:27:35','2011-09-22 12:27:35','','Introduction to Macroeconomic Aims','','inherit','open','open','','introduction-to-macroeconomic-aims-2','','','2011-09-22 20:27:35','2011-09-22 12:27:35','',1241,'',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2070,1,'2011-09-15 21:49:25','2011-09-15 13:49:25','<h3>You’re meant for big things. Challenge yourself. Teach more students than you’ve ever imagined.</h3>\r\nWar philosopher Clausewitz wrote in his magnum opus Vom Kriege, that “Everything is very simple in war, but the simplest thing is difficult.” This is true in teaching as well. The best way to inspire a student academically and develop his interest in a subject is to give the most enthralling lesson possible. However, even regular teachers falter before this task. Now imagine teaching thousands of students and capturing their attention. How would you do that? How would you impart the experiences and knowledge gained from years of schooling to your juniors?\r\n<blockquote>“One way of looking at this might be that for 42 years, I\'ve been making small, regular deposits in this bank of experience: education and training. And on January 15 the balance was sufficient so that I could make a very large withdrawal.”<br></br><small>Captain Sullenberger, pilot who landed the US Airway Flight 1549 in the Hudson River during an emergency</small></blockquote>\r\nHow would you make your withdrawal? We know that you do not want your time to be squandered meaninglessly. Through a combination of your own intellect and the generous endowments given to you by the education system, you became the best. Do you feel the need to give back something to your juniors - something less ephemeral than one passing lesson to a select group of students.\r\n\r\nWe can’t give you the answers, but if you found some yourself, we want to hear from you. Meet us for a cup of coffee (on us of course) and allow us to get to know you. We’ll help you get the meaningful teaching experience you deserve.','Graduates','','inherit','open','open','','965-revision-4','','','2011-09-15 21:49:25','2011-09-15 13:49:25','',965,'http://openlectures.sg/uncategorized/965-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(1324,1,'2011-09-22 20:28:18','2011-09-22 12:28:18','','Introduction to Economic Growth','','inherit','open','open','','introduction-to-economic-growth-2','','','2011-09-22 20:28:18','2011-09-22 12:28:18','',1243,'',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1326,1,'2011-09-22 20:29:41','2011-09-22 12:29:41','','Potential and Actual Growth Using ADAS','','inherit','open','open','','potential-and-actual-growth-using-adas-2','','','2011-09-22 20:29:41','2011-09-22 12:29:41','',1245,'',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1328,1,'2011-09-22 20:30:12','2011-09-22 12:30:12','','Circular Flow of Income','','inherit','open','open','','circular-flow-of-income-2','','','2011-09-22 20:30:12','2011-09-22 12:30:12','',1247,'',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1330,1,